sec.p:
With a wide direct bandgap of 3.1âeV, p-type transparent copper iodide (CuI) has attracted increasing attentions in recent years because of its relatively high hole mobility and large exciton binding energy (~62âmeV)4,5 CuI has a zincblende ground-state phase below 643âK6 and demonstrated versatility in a wide range of optoelectronic applications, e.g., as efficient hole-transport layer in solar cells7â10 thin film transistors11â13 p-n heterojunctions14â16 thermoelectrics17,18 and lasing devices19. The VBM of CuI mainly consists of Cu 3d and I 5p orbitals, while its conduction band minimum (CBM) is mostly composed of Cu 4âs states. Nominally undoped CuI exhibits a hole concentration N in the range of 1016â1020âcmâ3, mainly attributed to the energetically favored formation of copper vacancy (VCu) acceptors with rather low ionization energy Îµ(0/-) of ~44âmeV, while compensating donor native defects (e.g., VI, CuI, and Cui) have relatively high formation energies as the Fermi level EF approaches the VBM20. In comparison with most TCOs, CuI has a much larger VB dispersion, with a small hole effective mass mh*\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${m}_{h}^{*}$$\end{document}~0.3 m0. A record hole mobility Î¼ of ~43.9âcm2âVâ1âsâ1 in single-crystalline CuI has been reported21, which is two orders of magnitude higher than that of commonly used p-type NiO (Î¼â<â0.1âcm2âVâ1âsâ1)22â24 Appropriate extrinsic acceptor doping (e.g., by substituting the iodine with chalcogen impurities like S or Se) can be employed to further increase the p-type conductivity of CuI25,26 In the low excitation density (i.e., the density of photogenerated electron-hole pairs less than the corresponding Mott density) regime, the optical properties of CuI are dominated by excitonic transitions. For instance, the absorption spectrum exhibits two sharp peaks at ~3.06âeV (Z1,2 excitonic absorption related to the doubly degenerated VBM at the Î point) and ~3.7âeV (Z3 transition due to the split-off band), respectively27,28 while two prominent peaks at ~3.06âeV (corresponding to the free-exciton recombination) and ~2.95âeV (related to the bound exciton recombination or donor-acceptor pair recombination) respectively can be observed in photoluminescence (PL) measurements.

