				\begin{document}$${{F}_{p} < 2\;{{{{{\rm{mJ}}}}}}/{{{{{{\rm{cm}}}}}}}^{2},\, \lambda }_{p}=320\;{{{{{{\mathrm{nm}}}}}}}$$\end{document}) at the time delay of 5âps. Owing to the increased band filling with increasing Fp55, the PB peak in TA spectra shows a slight blue-shift (with energy difference ~10âmeV), meanwhile the high energy tails also become more prominent. In the initial cooling stage, carrier-phonon scattering plays the dominant role. Under high pump fluence, the cooling of hot carriers may slow down due to the effect of hot-phonon bottleneck, i.e., the excess hot-phonon population increases the phonon reabsorption and thus reduce the net cooling rate68,69. Since hot carriers occupy electronic states with relatively higher energies above the bandgap energy (i.e., 406ânm), it is preferable to study the decay kinetics of âA at a higher energy (e.g., 395ânm) in order to better understand the effect of hot-phonon bottleneck in the CuI thin film. FigureÂ 7b plots the decay kinetics of TA spectra probed at wavelength of 395ânm with different Fp as well as their fits by using Eq. (5, 6). Interestingly, the decay signal recorded at 395ânm can be fitted to a monoexponential decay model, with the time constant (corresponding to the major cooling process) increasing from ~1 to ~3.5âps as the Fp increases (see Supplementary TableÂ 1). Such increase in the time constant with the Fp is due to the effect of hot-phonon bottleneck. Based on a model calculation, Herrfurth et al. found that the relaxation of hot carriers in CuI is dominated by carrier-LO-phonon interaction and the hot-phonon effect can delay the relaxation process by few picoseconds70, which is in good agreement with our findings.Fig. 7Pump fluence dependent hot carrier cooling dynamics.
a Normalized TA spectra around the peak at 406ânm under different pump fluences with Î»pâ=â320ânm. b Kinetic profiles of 395ânm bleach under different pump fluences. c Normalized TA spectra at different time delays (Fp~0.13âmJ/cm2), with the high energy tails (between 3.1 and 3.4âeV) fitted by an exponential function corresponding to MaxwellâBoltzmann distribution to extract the hot carrier temperature TC. d The obtained TC as a function of time delay.

To better elucidate the hot carrier cooling dynamics, the carrier temperature as a function of time delay is calculated. The high energy tail of TA above the band edge (from 3.1 to 3.4âeV) reflects energy distribution of state filling by hot carriers. Once the thermalization is reached for the EHP, the carrier temperature can be estimated by fitting the TA spectra above the band edge in a certain energy range (e.g., 3.1â3.4âeV for our case as shown in Fig.Â 7c) using the relation â£â³Aâ£âexp((EfâE)/kBTC)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$|\triangle {{{{{\rm{A}}}}}}|\propto {{\exp }}(({E}_{f}-E)/{k}_{B}{T}_{C})$$\end{document}, where Ef is the quasi-Fermi level, kB is the Boltzmann constant, TC is the carrier temperature. FigureÂ 7d shows the TC for the as-grown CuI thin film under different pump fluences (with Î»pâ=â320ânm). For relatively low Fp (i.e., ~0.13âmJ/cm2), the initial TC cools down rapidly from ~700âK to ~RT within 3âps. As the Fp increases, the initial TC becomes higher with an increased cooling time constant ÏC due to the effect of hot-phonon bottleneck. For instance, ÏC is larger than 4âps for relatively high Fp (e.g.,â>0.64âmJ/cm2). Note that the obtained ÏC is larger than the time constant as given in Supplementary TableÂ 1, which can be ascribed to their different cooling processes included, i.e., the former process is related to carrier-phonon scattering and the phonon-phonon scattering, while the latter is mainly associated with the carrier-phonon scattering. With a high pump fluence, the TC also exhibits a slight rise at a time delay of ~10âps with the corresponding ÏCâ>â6âns, as indicated in Fig.Â 7d. Similar with the âA as shown in the inset of Fig.Â 4b, such slight rise in TC can be attributed to the aforementioned stimulated emission induced re-excitation, while the relatively long ÏC most likely results from the Auger heating when the photogenerated carrier density is high58.

Two phase-coherent photons with hÎ½â<âEg can be absorbed cooperatively in semiconductors, and thus the electron-hole pairs can be generated by such two-photon absorption (2PA) process. 2PA has been found in different semiconductors (e.g., ZnO, Î²-Ga2O3, GaAs etc)71,72. For instance, two-photon and three-photon absorptions in ZnO were attributed to the defect-states-mediated multiphoton absorption process72. In order to investigate the possible 2PA in the CuI thin film, the fs-TA measurements were also carried out with the pump excitation energies less than the EG of CuI. FigureÂ 8a shows the TA spectra of CuI film under different Fp with Î»pâ=â520ânm and ÏDâ=â0.5âps. As seen, the magnitudes of both the high energy tail (due to the band filling) and the low energy tail (due to the PIA) increase as the Fp increases, analogous to the TA spectra under excitation energyâ>âEG. Similar phenomena are also observed for TA spectra under pump excitation with longer Î»p (e.g., 600ânm). 2PA is a third-order nonlinear process and is highly dependent on the intensity of the excitation beam, in which the attenuation is proportional to the square of the laser intensity73. The measured |âA| signal (recorded at 5âps after excitation) shows a linear dependence with the square of pump fluence Fp (see the inset of Fig.Â 8b), further verifying the photoexcitation via 2PA process. The closed-aperture Z-scan measurement was also performed to investigate the 2PA process. As illustrated in Fig.Â 8c, the corresponding Z-scan trace shows a distinct valley at zâ=â0, confirming the existence of 2PA.Fig. 8Ultrafast carrier dynamics in two-photon absorption.
a TA spectra of as-grown CuI thin film under different pump fluences at a time delay of 0.5âps with Î»pâ=â520ânm, and b corresponding kinetic traces at 406ânm with the best fitting (solid line). Inset in b shows the measured |âA| signal (recorded at 5âps) with quadratic scaling of the pump pulse fluence Fp with the linear fit (dotted line). c Z-scan of the as-grown CuI thin film under excitation with Î»pâ=â800ânm and Fpâ=â3.2âmJ/cm2. dlnnâln(n0)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
