In conclusion, we comprehensively investigated the optoelectronic properties and the ultrafast carrier dynamics of CuI thin films. The as-grown CuI thin film exhibits hole concentration N~9âÃâ1019âcmâ3, and the N decreases (increases) to ~3âÃâ1019âcmâ3 (~1.2âÃâ1020âcmâ3) after PTA in air (I2). The free holes can be primarily attributed to shallow native acceptors (e.g., VCu, Ii) in the CuI thin films. PTA treatments in air facilitates the formation of native donor defects (e.g., VI, Cui, VIâ+âCui defect clusters). The absorption spectra indicate that the excitonic feature of CuI maintains at a high carrier density up to ~5âÃâ1019âcmâ3 owing to the possible formation of Mahan excitons at RT. PL measurements reveal that the emission peak at ~420ânm is most likely due to the radiative (e, VCu0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${V}_{{{{{{\rm{Cu}}}}}}}^{0}$$\end{document}) recombination. Femtosecond transient absorption (fs-TA) measurements were carried out to understand the ultrafast carrier dynamics in these CuI thin films. Through carrier-carrier scattering, quasi-equilibrium distribution of photogenerated carriers is rapidly built up (<200âfs) within the time resolution of our TA setup. For relatively high excitation density (>1019âcmâ3), the EHP underwent a fast Auger recombination (with Auger recombination coefficient of ~7.42âÃâ10â30âcm6/s) in the initial decay process with a time delayâ<â5â6âps, while the carrier cooling rate (with cooling time ~6âns) slows down notably due to the effects of hot-phonon bottleneck as well as the Auger heating. Interestingly, a re-excitation was also found at a time delay ~25âps, which is most probably due to the stimulated emission from the degenerate EHP. As in the case of medium excitation density (1018â1019âcmâ3), the photogenerated carriers rapidly cool down with a cooling timeâ<â3âps, and the initial recombination is governed by the trap-assisted SRH process (with the SRH recombination coefficient of ~2.42âÃâ1011âsâ1). When the excitation density is relatively low (<1018âcmâ3), the SRH recombination plays the major role in the initial decay process with a time delayâ<â6âps, followed by a radiative exciton recombination (with recombination coefficient of ~6.4âÃâ1010âsâ1) at a time delay in the range of 6â20âps. As the time delay is >20âps, the recombination kinetics is dominated by the radiative bimolecular recombination process (with recombination coefficient of ~1.3âÃâ10â11âcm3âsâ1). As increasing of excess carrier density, recombination coefficients linked to the SRH recombination, bimolecular recombination and Auger recombination decrease, while the radiative exciton recombination coefficient is nearly constant. Two-photon absorption in the CuI thin films was verified from the fs-TA measurements as well as the Z-scan measurements. Two-photon induced ultrafast carrier dynamics was also discussed. CuI thin films with different PTA treatments show distinct defect-related recombination behaviors, i.e., the nonradiative recombination in the CuI thin film PTA in air is accelerated by deep defects via the trap-assisted Auger recombination, while the radiative (e, VCu0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
